        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(zai): send current GLM thinking params",
        "body": "Closes #97772\n\n## What Problem This Solves\n\nFixes an issue where users enable reasoning on Z.ai GLM models but OpenClaw sends the stale `enable_thinking` payload field, so current GLM reasoning mode is not activated for GLM-5.2 and no `reasoning_content` is returned.\n\n## Why This Change Was Made\n\nThe OpenAI-compatible completions formatter now emits the current Z.ai thinking payload shape, `thinking: { type: \"enabled\" | \"disabled\" }`, instead of the legacy `enable_thinking` field. The shared Z.ai mapping lives with the OpenAI-compatible completions provider and is used by both request builders, so the normal stream path and the managed provider-transport path stay aligned.\n\nGLM-5.2 receives the provider-supported `reasoning_effort` values (`high` or `max`) when thinking is enabled. `minimal`, `none`, and off-style requests send disabled thinking without `reasoning_effort`, and binary Z.ai thinking models such as GLM-5.1 keep the on/off payload without an unsupported effort field.\n\n## User Impact\n\nZ.ai GLM-5.2 users can turn reasoning on and have OpenClaw send the request shape expected by the current Z.ai API. Existing binary thinking models keep their current behavior and do not receive extra unsupported `reasoning_effort` parameters.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Claim proved: both OpenAI-compatible completions request builders use `thinking.type`, never `enable_thinking`, for Z.ai thinking mode; GLM-5.2 maps enabled low-style levels to `reasoning_effort: \"high\"`, strongest OpenClaw effort to `\"max\"`, treats `minimal`/`none` as disabled thinking, and does not add `reasoning_effort` for binary GLM-5.1.\n- Commands / artifacts:\n  - `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/llm/providers/openai-completions.test.ts src/agents/openai-transport-stream.test.ts` -> 2 Vitest shards passed; 39 + 285 tests passed.\n  - `./node_modules/.bin/oxfmt --check --threads=1 src/llm/providers/openai-completions-zai-thinking.ts src/agents/openai-transport-stream.ts src/agents/openai-transport-stream.test.ts src/llm/providers/openai-completions.ts src/llm/providers/openai-completions.test.ts packages/llm-core/src/types.ts` -> all matched files use the correct format.\n  - `git diff --check` -> no whitespace errors.\n  - `python .agents\\skills\\autoreview\\scripts\\autoreview --mode local` -> clean, no accepted/actionable findings reported.\n  - Live provider proof on current PR head `6b59fe2a95773c2bc8843fa3a0b041846b3eca20`: a local script invoked the real `streamOpenAICompletions` path against the official BigModel/Z.ai OpenAI-compatible endpoint `https://open.bigmodel.cn/api/paas/v4` with `model=glm-5.2`, `reasoningEffort=low`, and a short arithmetic prompt.\n- Observed result:\n  - Focused payload tests intercept the legacy `streamOpenAICompletions` request body before network and directly inspect `buildOpenAICompletionsParams` for the managed transport path, verifying the current Z.ai thinking fields and effort gating in both builders.\n  - Live request proof returned HTTP 200 from `POST /chat/completions` with `content-type: text/event-stream;charset=UTF-8`.\n  - Live captured request summary: `thinking: { type: \"enabled\" }`, `reasoning_effort: \"high\"`, and `has_enable_thinking: false`.\n  - Live parsed response summary: `stopReason: \"stop\"`, content types included both `thinking` and `text`, one thinking block was present with `thinkingSignature: \"reasoning_content\"`, the visible final answer was correct, and usage was 35 input tokens / 18 output tokens / 53 total tokens. The actual reasoning text and API key are not included in the PR body.\n- ClawSweeper follow-up handled: added managed OpenAI-completions transport coverage, changed `minimal`/`none` to disabled thinking with no `reasoning_effort`, and kept the shared helper under the provider layer to avoid widening the agents surface.\n- Not tested / proof gaps: live proof used the official BigModel/Z.ai OpenAI-compatible GLM-5.2 endpoint rather than the overseas `api.z.ai` host because the available credential is a BigModel key. The request/response contract is the same documented GLM-5.2 thinking contract this PR targets.\n\n## AI Assistance\n\nAI-assisted: yes. Codex inspected the issue, checked duplicate PR coverage, implemented the focused fix, ran validation, addressed autoreview findings, updated the PR after ClawSweeper feedback, and ran the redacted live provider proof after the user supplied a local BigModel API key through the environment.",
